<HEAD>Rewards Offered To Reduce Vandalism In Helsinki</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a bid to reduce vandalism, the city
is offering small rewards for help in catching people who deface or
damage public property.
   For one year beginning next month, the city will give $120
rewards to people who help police catch vandals, according to
Finnish newspapers and English-language ``wanted'' posters seen in
downtown Helsinki this week.
   ``We chose English for the posters because `wanted' is such a
well-known word,'' city spokesman Pertti Mustonen told The
Associated Press. Finland has two official languages, Finnish and
Swedish.
   Mustonen said the defacement or destruction of telephone booths,
public transportation vehicles and other city property costs
$950,000 a year.
</TEXT>
