<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Sebastian     02-18 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Sebastian,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shopkeeper Near Hearst Castle Served Likes of Winston Churchill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPLETON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. ``Pete'' Sebastian, who served the
likes of Winston Churchill and Cary Grant at his store outside the
gates of Hearst's Castle in the 1930s and 1940s, has died at the
age of 81.
   Sebastian died Wednesday at Twin Cities Hospital of a heart
attack, said his daughter, Mary Sebastian Hansen of Boca Raton, Fla.
   In addition to running the store bearing his name, he served the
tiny, rolling hills community of San Simeon as its postmaster,
notary public and registrar of voters.
   The general store, which included gas pumps, a coffee shop and
post office, is registered as a state historical monument, Ms.
Hansen said.
   Sebastian worked as a landscaper around San Francisco publisher
William Randolph Hearst's art-bedecked mansion in the 1920s. Now a
museum run by the state Department of Parks and Recreation, the
sprawling home is one of the most popular tourist attractions in
California.
   Hearst, founder of the newspaper chain that carries his name and
model for Orson Welles' classic movie ``Citizen Kane,'' often
entertained celebrities and business and government notables at the
hilltop mansion.
   Churchill, Grant and playwright George Bernard Shaw were among
the many prominent visitors to the store Sebastian took over from
his father in 1933. He sold the shop in 1971 and retired, said Bob
Buddell, the store's present owner.
   Sebastian told an interviewer in 1986 that he always considered
the Hearsts neighbors, dating back to the pre-castle days when they
stayed in the Hotel Bayview next to his family's store.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
