<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhonyJuice     02-18 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phony Juice,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guilty Verdicts In Phony Juice Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former executives of the Beech-Nut
Nutritional Corp. face substantial prison terms and fines after
being convicted of selling flavored sugar water labeled as apple
juice for babies.
   Former Beech-Nut president Neils L. Hoyvald and a former vice
president, John F. Lavery, were charged with hundreds of violations
of federal food and drug laws along with conspiracy and mail fraud.
   Lavery was convicted Wednesday of all 448 counts in the
indictment, said federal prosecutor Thomas Roche.
   Hoyvald was found guilty on 351 counts of violating federal food
and drug laws; the jury, however, could not reach a verdict on
about 80 other counts against him, including conspiracy and mail
fraud, Roche said.
   The maximum penalty for conspiracy is five years in prison and a
$10,000 fine; for mail fraud, five years and $1,000; and for food
and drug law violations, three years and $10,000, Roche said.
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas C. Platt did not set a date for
sentencing, but it should be within six to eight weeks, Roche said.
   Roche said both Hoyvald and Lavery, who were allowed to remain
free on bail until sentencing, face ``substantial prison terms and
substantial fines.'' It is likely, however, that they would serve
concurrent sentences.
   Lawyers for both men declined to comment on the verdict but said
they would appeal the convictions.
   Roche called the result of the three-month trial ``an important
victory for consumers.
   The corporation, which also was named in the November 1986
indictments, pleaded guilty last year, a fact the judge withheld
from the jury.
   Beech-Nut, a subsidiary of Nestle Inc. and based in Fort
Washington, Pa., agreed to pay a $2 million fine, and also settled
a class-action suit by agreeing to set up a $5 million cash fund
for consumers and to provide $2.5 million in Beech-Nut and
affiliated products to retailers.
   The indictment charged that Beech-Nut shipped adulterated juice
throughout the United States and overseas from 1978 to 1983. No
evidence was presented that the juice caused any health problems.
   Hoyvald's attorney, Brendan Sullivan Jr., urged the jury not to
believe the testimony of two key prosecution witnesses who work for
Beech-Nut that they had repeatedly warned executives that the
concentrate used to make the produce contained little or no apple
juice.
   Steven Kimelman, Lavery's attorney, said his client was ``a man
who had nothing to gain by committing a crime.'' Lavery was in
charge of manufacturing at the Canajoharie plant in western New
York, where the product was bottled.
</TEXT>
