<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSPrinciples     02-18 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Principles,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Companies Endorse Active Role In AIDS Education</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the nation's biggest corporations have
endorsed a so-called workplace bill of rights, pledging to actively
educate workers about AIDS and protect the rights of employees who
have the deadly disease.
   The pledge unveiled Wednesday by the Citizens Commission on AIDS
for New York City and Northern New Jersey says people with AIDS or
exposed to the suspected AIDS virus ``are entitled to the same
rights and opportunities as people with other serious or
life-threatening illnesses.''
   The pledge endorsed by 30 employers adds that they ``do not pose
a risk of transmission of the virus to coworkers through ordinary
workplace contact.''
   Requiring workers or job applicants take blood tests for the
virus is specifically rejected, as is divulging medical information
about an employee, it says.
   But, it said, ``Employers should provide employees with
sensitive, accurate and up-to-date education about risk reduction
in their personal lives.''
   IBM was the first company to endorse the principles, John
Zucotti, cochairman of the commission, said at a news conference.
   Others are AT&T, Time Inc., Johnson & Johnson, Warner-Lambert,
ITT, Dow Jones, Chemical Bank, the city of New York, the teachers'
unions of New York City and Newark, N.J., United Jersey Banks,
Shubert Organization, Times Mirror Co., Atlantic Industries; Ms.,
Atlantic, Sassy and U.S. News and World Report magazines;
   Rubenstein Associates, Rockefeller Brothers Fund, the National
Urban League, the Girl Scouts, Salvation Army, Red Cross of Greater
New York, New Jersey A. Philip Randolph Institute, Lambda Legal
Defense and Education Fund, Fund for the City of New York, Wildcat
Services and Archie Comics.
   ``Those companies that have subscribed to these principles have
been very courageous,'' said Thomas Stoddard, executive director of
the Lambda fund. ``They have been willing to take the heat because
they understand the gravity of the problem. We will continue to
have the problem of stigmatization until all companies subscribe to
these principles.''
   The 15-member commission was established in July and funded by
17 local foundations. Zucotti said its mission is to marshal
information and mobilize effort to improve care for AIDS sufferers,
promote prevention and education about the fatal affliction and
address its social impact.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. There is no known cure.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   The federal Centers for Disease Control estimates that AIDS will
strike 270,000 Americans and kill 179,000 by the end of 1991. The
CDC already has received reports of more than 28,000 deaths of
people with AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
