<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PamperedBabies     02-18 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pampered Babies,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Selectmen Ban Purchase Of Disposable Diapers By Welfare Recipients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies whose parents receive a form of
welfare in this southern Maine community won't be ``Pampered''
anymore.
   Selectmen have decided that residents who receive general
assistance, a local form of welfare, cannot use the money to
purchase disposable diapers.
   ``Cloth diapers will be less expensive for the taxpayers,''
Chairwoman Jean Harris said.
   Harris said disposable diapers can cost more than $10 a box, and
some mothers buy up to four boxes each week.
   Selectman W. Robert Donovan was the lone dissenter in Tuesday's
3-1 vote on the issue. ``I'd just like to say, it's not the
1950s,'' he said.
   Local selectmen are permitted to decide how general assistance
recipients can spend the funds. Generally, the money is used for
housing, food, heating, health care and other life essential items.
   About 400 residents will take advantage of Lisbon's $30,000
general assistance fund this year, Town Manager John Baubier said
Thursday.
</TEXT>
