<1ST_LINE>r a AM-7-UpRuling     02-18 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-7-Up Ruling,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Award Reduced From $10.5 million to $375,000 for Woman Struck by
Bottle Cap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIRK MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Wednesday reduced the award to an
83-year-old woman struck in the eye by a soda bottle cap from $10.5
million granted by a jury to $375,000.
   Third District Judge Kenneth Rigtrup said that jurors were
``inflamed with passion'' when they recently made the award to Mae
L. Roberts of Holladay.
   ``The award of $10 million appears to be disproportionate and
unreasonable,'' Rigtrup said at a post-trial hearing. He awarded
$75,000 in compensatory and $300,000 in punitive damages.
   Roberts was struck in the eye when an aluminum twist cap blew
off a 7-Up bottle she was opening. As a result of the injury, the
sight in Roberts' left eye was impaired.
   Rigtrup said Roberts could accept his judgment, request a new
trial within 15 days or appeal the decision.
   Although there was no evidence that Roberts' means of support
was damaged by the accident, the judge said, 7-Up's actions
warranted a judgment for significant injury to her eye.
   The company knew of the potential danger caused by the bottle
caps since the late 1960s and has ``irresponsibly'' not remedied
the problem, Rigtrup said.
   In arguing for 7-Up, Robert Henderson said new owners and
management are concerned about the bottle cap problem and have
taken steps to address the issue, but solutions do not come swiftly.
   He said between 1986 and 1988 the company knew of only one
incident in which someone was injured with a bottle cap.
   Henderson acknowledged 7-Up is partly to blame for the accident,
but the fact that Roberts' was attempting to open the bottle with
pliers shows that she also was at fault.
   Defense attorney Colin King said he will discuss the possibility
of an appeal and said his ``spunky'' client just may seek a new
trial, despite her age.
   ``I'm as shocked about the judge's decision as I was with 7-Up's
refusal to adjust the problem (caused by unsafe bottle caps),''
Roberts said. ``This is a sad day for consumers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
