<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Walesa-Australia     02-18 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walesa-Australia,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Hopes to Travel to Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and three
aides will apply to travel to Australia next month to attend an
international trade union meeting, a spokesman for the banned
Polish union said Wednesday.
   Spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said Walesa has been invited to
Melbourne on March 14-18 to attend the World Congress of the
International Confederation of Free Trade Unions.
   The invitation was extended by the Australian Confederation of
Trade Unions, Onyszkiewicz said.
   Contacted at home in Gdansk, Walesa said he received the
invitation and would like to make the trip, but declined further
comment.
   Walesa, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1983, has not left
Poland since the union was declared illegal after the 1981
imposition of martial law. He once applied for a passport to travel
abroad but did not receive it for ``technical reasons,'' Walesa
said.
   Onyszkiewicz said Walesa would complete his passport application
for the Australian trip very soon, but the spokesman said he was
not optimistic it would be granted.
   Three other Solidarity leaders also hope to make the trip, said
Onyszkiewicz. They are Bogdan Lis, Wladyslaw Frasyniuk and
Bronislaw Geremek.
</TEXT>
