<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--CattleGenetics     02-18 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cattle Genetics,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Announces Method of Determining Sex of Cattle in the
Embryo</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A biotechnology company said Wednesday it has
developed a 95 percent accurate method of determining the sex of
calves in the embryo.
   ``This embryo-sexing technique makes it possible to control the
composition of the herd,'' said Joseph M. Massey, president of
Granada Genetics Inc.
   The technique involves removing a few cells from the cow embryo
and examining them with a gene probe capable of detecting the Y
chromosome, which is present only in male cells and indicates a
male embryo, the company said.
   Embryos designated male or female can then be shipped to clients
for transplantation, the company said.
   Producing cattle of the desired sex has obvious advantages to
dairy farmers, who need only females, Massey said. Because of
widespread use of artificial insemination, one bull can sire
thousands of calves.
</TEXT>
