<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 0341EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SteeplePeople Bjt   02-18 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steeple People, Bjt,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Pinnacle Of Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They call themselves ``The Steeple
People,'' and their creations can be found reaching for the sky
from Alaska to Saudi Arabia.
   Jerry Bennett has been one of them since his college days when
he took a part-time job to help pay for his education. Today, at
48, he is president and co-owner.
   ``There aren't many things we can't do when it comes to
steeples,'' said Bennett. ``We also specialize in cupolas, crosses,
towers, or anything else needed to decorate a church or a
building.''
   Campbellsville Industries' products are shipped everywhere and
may range from six feet to 229-feet, which is the size of what
Bennett calls the world's largest prefabricated steeple.
   ``We're trying to get it included in the Guinness Book of
Records,'' Bennett said, adding that the $350,000 project was built
for the First Baptist Church of Huntsville, Ala.
   Other installations include the Baptist Pavilion at the 1982
World's Fair in Knoxville; the Solidarity Tower replica in Chicago;
and reproduction of the West Bridgewater, Mass., steeple, which was
originally constructed during Paul Revere's time.
   ``The order from Saudi Arabia called for a cupola for a
waterworks system.''
   Bennett's plant, located 80 miles from Louisville, has 85
employees, including six draftsmen who will furnish a design if the
customer doesn't know in advance what he wants.
   The company mails out more than one million pieces of
advertising annually, but Bennett said he also gets sales from the
interstates.
   ``Somebody will see our trucks, loaded with steeples or cupolas,
and then telephone us to ask, `How do I get one of those things?' ''
   His crews do a lot of driving. Several years ago, they made four
1,200 mile trips to New Haven, Conn., to erect a spire on a Roman
Catholic landmark there.
   Bennett became involved with steeples after Campbellsville
College set up a small industry complex on campus to help students
with their finances.
   ``I was among those who were able to work with wood or metal,
turning out items that could be marketed for a nominal profit.''
   Later, Bennett taught art in high school but returned to the
college as a full-time employee handling designs and sales for the
complex.
   In 1969, Campbellsville College sold the business to a private
individual who kept it 10 years before he was bought out by Bennett
and three other employees.
   Although the company is diversified, steeples still account for
60 to 70 percent of sales. They also have caused a few embarrassing
moments.
   Bennett recalled the time that a contractor in Virginia
purchased a steeple and gave ``our deliveryman vague instructions
about reaching the church where it was to be installed.''
   The spire went to another church and the contractor showed up
the next morning to retrieve it.
   Before he could say anything, the excited minister told him:
   ``We have been praying for new pews and an anonymous donor
provided them.
   ``We prayed for new carpet and got it anonymously.
   ``The last item we wanted was a new steeple. Last night, the
Lord put it in our front yard.''
   The contractor explained the mixup and admitted later to Bennett
that ``it was the hardest thing I've ever done.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880218-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 0345EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     02-18 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed In Slow Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices remain mostly lower amid sluggish
demand and adequate supplies.
   At the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for March
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
closed Wednesday at $16.61 per 41-gallon barrel, down 6 cents from
Tuesday.
   Among refined products, wholesale contracts for unleaded
gasoline closed at 46.66 cents a gallon, up 0.37 cent, while
wholesale heating oil was down 0.79 cent at 45.58 cents a gallon.
   A trade report published late Tuesday stimulated an early rally,
because the numbers showed sharp drawdowns of gasoline and heating
oil supplies, as well as a cutback of refinery use in the week
ended Friday, analysts said.
   They said the figures _ released by the Washington-based
American Petroleum Institute _ led many traders to believe that
prices would increase, as existing demand chased tigher supplies.
   But the gains turned into losses, ``once people realized that
the stocks were moving from primary storage into secondary storage
in anticipation of the tugboat strike in New York harbor,'' said
Donald Morton, an analyst at the Boston office of Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   ``The market closed at its low in fairly light volume,'' he
added.
   Morton said dealers were having the products shipped from New
York to Boston and other markets to ensure continued access.
   A union representing 2,500 tugboat and barge crew members went
on strike against nine towing companies on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
