<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Northwest-Strike Bjt   02-18 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest-Strike, Bjt,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union: Northwest Flight Attendants Will Strike if No Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' 6,500 flight
attendants will vote to strike on Feb. 26 if they haven't reached
agreement on a new contract, Teamsters union officials say.
   About 300 flight attendants with the Eagan, Minn.-based airline
began the strike authorization vote Tuesday during a union meeting
in Bloomington. Results of the voting, which will continue through
Saturday in Minneapolis and St. Paul, Minn., and five other U.S.
cities, are expected to be announced at a strike rally Monday
night, Teamsters Local 2747 officials said Wednesday.
   Strike authorization requires a two-thirds majority of the
membership.
   In the last strike against Northwest, the machinists union
walked out for 27 days in May 1982.
   The two sides have not negotiated since the National Mediation
Board released them from mandatory negotiations last month because
they were deadlocked over wages, fringe benefits and work rules. A
30-day cooling-off period ends Feb. 26.
   A federal mediator is expected to bring the two sides together
again next week, although no date has been set.
   Northwest officials said they are determined to keep flying if a
strike occurs. About 2,000 Northwest managers are qualified to be
flight attendants and would be used during a strike, said Northwest
spokesman Redmond Tyler. Northwest also has advertised to recruit
replacement flight attendants over the past few weeks.
   But some travel agents are beginning to warn prospective
Northwest passengers of a possible strike.
   ``People are starting to ask about it, '' said Kevin Mossier,
president of the Travel Co., a Minneapolis-St. Paul travel agency.
   Northwest, which merged with Republic Airlines in 1986, controls
about 60 percent of the Minneapolis-St. Paul passenger traffic. In
the event of a strike, United Airlines, the No. 2 carrier in the
Twin Cities, would bring in larger planes for Twin Cities flights,
according to United spokesman Matt Gonring in Chicago.
   On Tuesday, a federal judge in New York City ordered the
Teamsters local to reinstate Northwest flight attendants Guy Meek
and John Davis as members of the union's negotiating committee.
Meek and Davis formerly worked for Republic.
   The Teamsters must allow the two men to participate in
negotiations and vote on whether to send any contract offers to the
flight attendants for ratification, U.S. District Judge Joseph
McLaughlin ruled.
   Teamsters officials had ejected the two men from the bargaining
committee last fall, alleging that they tried to persuade 2,800
former Republic attendants not to pay union dues.
   Former Republic attendants said the Teamsters have urged them to
pay union dues voluntarily.
   It was not clear from the judge's order whether the Teamsters
can force the members to pay dues, but Teamsters spokesman Jeff
Musto said all flight attendants would be allowed to vote on the
strike authorization whether or not they were current on dues.
   On another front Tuesday, a federal judge in Minneapolis said
Northwest and its machinists union will have to arbitrate a
1{-year-old dispute over restoration of wage cuts granted by about
1,200 former Republic Airlines employees.
   U.S. District Judge David Doty dismissed a lawsuit brought by
District Lodge 143 of the International Association of Machinists
in November 1986 and refused to order Northwest to pay the higher
wages.
   The dispute, which involves mechanics, stock clerks, plane
cleaners, custodians and clerical workers who granted wage
concessions to Republic, should be resolved by an arbitrator, not a
federal judge, Doty ruled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880218-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 0403EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Black&Decker     02-18 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black & Decker,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black & Decker Rebuffed Again In American Standard Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black & Decker Corp. has been rebuffed again
in its attempt to make personal contact with the top management of
American Standard Inc., which is the target of a takeover bid by
Black & Decker.
   In a filing Wednesday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the power tool and home appliance maker said Chairman
Nolan B. Archibald attempted to telephone American Standard
Chairman William B. Boyd on Feb. 11.
   ``Unfortunately, as has been the case throughout, Mr. Boyd
wouldn't take the call,'' said Black & Decker spokeswoman Barbara
Lucas.
   Archibald wanted to reconfirm his company's ``strong desire to
arrange a one-on-one meeting with Mr. Boyd to negotiate a business
combination between Black & Decker and the company, and to advise
Mr. Boyd that he was willing to make major concessions in order to
consummate a friendly transaction, including a preemptive price,
board seats and financial arrangements for employees of the
company,'' Ms. Lucas said.
   ``The message was no different from the one we've been leaving
all along,'' she said.
   ``We think the price of $65 (a share) was a preemptive price,''
she said. The Towson, Md.-based manufacturer will consider raising
that price, ``only on the basis of information that we haven't seen
yet.''
   However, the SEC filing should not be taken as a sign that Black
& Decker is willing to raise the price, she stressed.
   American Standard has urged its shareholders to reject Black &
Decker's $2.1 billion hostile takeover. The New York-based maker of
plumbing, heating and air conditioning equipment has also adopted a
``poison pill'' defense that allows its shareholders to buy back
shares of the surviving company at half their market value.
   American Standard also has said it is considering alternatives
to the bid, including a restructuring, leveraged buyout or a
friendly merger with another company.
   Black & Decker, which originally bid $56 a share for American
Standard stock, said last week it had obtained bank financing for
the deal.
</TEXT>
