<2ND_LINE>PM-Flight Attendants,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President of Flight Attendants Union Suggests Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Association of
Flight Attendants urged the Federal Aviation Administration to
tighten its regulation of the airline industry.
   ``Passengers' first priority should be to insist that the FAA
promote safety over profit, rebuild the inspector workforce and
place tighter controls on the number of flights until the air
traffic controller workforce is rebuilt,'' Susan Bianchi-Sand said
at a news conference Wednesday.
   Ms. Bianchi-Sand proposed reforms that she said were inexpensive
ways to improve cabin safety.
   ``All that is needed is a will to make flying truly safe,'' the
union president said. ``We have learned from emergency after
emergency that changes are needed.''
   Ms. Bianchi-Sand said the FAA should update its standards to
require passenger seats that do not break loose in a crash, require
life vests on more planes, and limit the hours that flight
attendants can work.
   Ms. Bianchi-Sand said the FAA also should resist industry
pressure to repeal a ruling that would require improved cabin
materials and reduce the threat of toxic smoke.
   ``Where costs are involved, the industry is almost shameless,''
she said.
</TEXT>
