<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated     02-18 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau Increases Pressure On Federated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. has intensified the pressure on
Federated Department Stores Inc. by boosting its tender offer for
the giant retailer to $61 a share.
   Federated, meanwhile, continued to look into ways of avoiding a
hostile takeover.
   Campeau's amended offer came Wednesday a day after the Federated
board of directors rejected the Toronto developer's previous
proposal to pay $66 a share in a definitive merger agreement. The
board had questioned whether Campeau had the necessary financial
backing to complete the $5.85 billion deal.
   Campeau said it would further sweeten its bid to $66 if
Federated agreed to be acquired by midnight Sunday. The company was
only willing to pay $66 a share if Federated management agreed to
go along voluntarily. Campeau is offering a lower price if
Federated management resists.
   Instead of accepting the tender offer, the Federated directors
decided on a restructuring that could include retaining Federated's
department stores and selling its other assets, the company said.
   The latest rebuff by Federated's directors did not deter
Campeau, which said Wednesday it has the necessary financing to buy
Federated.
   Campeau's latest tender offer of $61 a share amounts to about
$5.4 billion, a sharp increase from the $47 a share, or roughly
$4.2 billion, it initially offered on Jan. 25. Federated rejected
the original tender offer as inadequate.
   Federated stock fell $2 to $61.75 a share in New York Stock
Exchange trading Wednesday.
   Federated also twice rejected Campeau's alternative offer for a
definitive merger agreement, including offers of $61 and $66 per
share, because it questioned Campeau's ability to complete such a
deal.
   However, Campeau spokeswoman Joele Frank said in New York
Wednesday that ``financing for a $66 bid is absolutely solid.''
   Federated managers are looking into other options, such as
selling to other unspecified interested parties, issuing perferred
stock and buying back more than half of Federated's 88.5 million
shares.
   Analysts said it was unclear how Federated might proceed if it
chooses to sell its non-department store assets.
   ``A lot depends on whether they sell them to someone outright or
spin them off'' through a public stock offering, said Thomas
Tashjian, an analyst with the Los Angeles investment firm of
Seidler Amdec Securities Inc.
   Federated operates about 650 stores in 36 states and had sales
exceeding $11 billion last year. Its holdings include
Bloomingdale's and Abraham and Straus, both based in New York;
Filene's of Boston; Burdines of Miami; Rich's in Atlanta; Bullock's
and Bullock's-Wilshire in Los Angeles; I. Magnin in San Francisco;
and Lazarus in Ohio.
   The company could be considering selling chains such as its
Ralphs grocery stores, Main Street soft-goods stores, Gold Circle
discount stores and Children's Place clothing stores, industry
observers said.
   Federated's directors said a shareholders' rights plan adopted
by the board last month would take effect Thursday. The plan, known
as a ``poison pill'' defense, is designed to discourage an unwanted
takeover by making such a move more expensive.
   Federated spent last weekend negotiating with numerous parties,
including Campeau, which bought Allied Stores Corp. in December
1986. Among those believed to be interested is the takeover
specialist firm Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Co., based in New York.
   Campeau's upgraded tender offer Wednesday includes a provision
that recently enacted anti-takeover legislation would have to be
invalidated. Campeau is challenging anti-takeover measures in
Delaware and Ohio.
   Cincinnati-based Federated could be covered by both
anti-takeover measures because it is based in Ohio and is
incorporated in Delaware.
</TEXT>
