<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Britain-Ford 1stLd-Writethru f0019 02-18 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Ford, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Returns Indicate Contract Approval of Ford Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with early returns indicating
contract approval, eight plants voting to return to work. Picks up
4th graf pvs, The settlement ... A version moving on general news
wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early returns in voting today by 32,000 striking
empoyees from Ford Motor Co.'s British plants indicated strong
approval of a new two-year contract, the company said.
   ``We are greatly encouraged by the voting figures coming in,''
said a Ford spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``There
have been some big swings in favor of accepting the offer, compared
to voting on the last offer, which was turned down.''
   The final results were to be released on Friday, but the
spokesman said hourly workers from at least eight of Ford's 22
British plants voted to accept the contract.
   The strike, which began Feb. 8, prompted the layoff of more than
9,700 workers. It disrupted production at a Ford plant at Genk,
Belgium, and threatened production at Ford plants in Spain and West
Germany, which rely on parts made at the British plants.
   The settlement was worked out in negotiations Tuesday between
company and union officials. If accepted, operations at Ford's
British plants could resume Monday.
   Shop stewards representing 8,000 Ford workers at the
traditionally militant Halewood plant near Liverpool in northwest
England on Wednesday recommended rejection of the offer.
   Peter Moore, a local union official at Halewood, said: ``We feel
there should be more money on offer, but we are also concerned that
plants on the Continent are getting improvements in hours and
holidays and we won't be getting that for another two years.''
   Shop stewards at a Ford engine-manufacturing plant in Bridgend,
Wales, recommended acceptance, saying they believed the company had
made significant concessions. That plant employs 1,300 hourly
workers.
   The Financial Times, Britain's leading business daily, said in
today's editions that the strikers seemed set to accept the deal,
although possibly by a narrow margin. The British Broadcasting
Corp. said the deal appeared likely to gain at least 60 percent
support.
   Ford backed down on its demand for a three-year contract,
offering instead a two-year pact with wage increases of at least 14
percent over the term of the contract. A Ford assembly worker in
Britain now earns a basic $320 a week.
   The unions agreed to changes in working practices designed to
increase productivity, but the changes must be agreed upon at the
plant level instead of being imposed by management.
   Legislator Barry Porter of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
governing Conservative Party on Wednesday condemned the proposed
settlement.
   ``It is quite clear that other industrial unions will take this
climbdown by the management as their bench mark for their claims in
the future. This has national implications in relation to the
government's fight against inflation,'' he said.
   Britain's annual inflation rate is now 3.3 percent. This is the
lowest it has been since October 1986.
   The government introduced tough measure to curb the once
powerful unions and the last major industrial strike in Britain was
a yearlong walkout by more than 90,000 coal miners in 1984-1985.
   But the Ford strike, a walkout by English Channel ferry crews,
and unrest in the state-run National Health Service and elsewhere
prompted fears in some quarters that they could herald a new wave
of industrial strife and an explosion in pay demands.
   Ford's British workers last walked out for nine weeks in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
