<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean prices fell on profit-taking from Wednesday's sharp
gains and in reaction to an increase in farmer selling of soybeans,
analysts said.
   Soybean futures advanced as much as 13} cents a bushel
Wednesday, partly in reaction to a Paul Harvey radio commentary
about a ``sudden-death syndrome'' affecting soybean crops. The
story turned out to be based on research findings that were first
reported nearly two years ago.
   Speculative buying limited the losses in soybeans this morning,
said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for the
investment firm Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``The market's not breaking as much as it could have, so there's
some underlying strength,'' Loewy said.
   Corn prices also retreated on increased farmer sales, while
wheat prices declined in follow-through selling from Wednesday,
analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.26\ a bushel; corn was } cent
to 2\ cents lower with March at $2.00\ a bushel; oats were } cent
lower to { cent higher with March at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were
2{ cents to 3{ cents lower with March at $6.30 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed to lower in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .08 cent higher with February
at 71.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .45 cent
lower with March at 83.42 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .42
cent lower with February at 46.85 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .28 cent to .48 cent higher with February at 56.00
cents a pound.
   Live cattle futures advanced on Wednesday while other livestock
and meat futures settled mostly lower.
</TEXT>
