<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 1219EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Lomas&Nettleton     02-18 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Lomas & Nettleton,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lomas & Nettleton To Lay Off 500 Workers Nationwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lomas & Nettleton Financial Corp., citing a
downturn in the nation's housing market, says it plans to shut down
half its mortgage banking operations and cut about 20 percent of
its workforce.
   The Dallas company, which is the nation's largest independent
mortgage banker, said it would take a $93 million charge in the
current quarter as a result of its restructuring plans.
   Lomas said it expects to lose about $69 million for the three
fiscal quarters ended March 31 and about $55 million for the year.
   Lomas President James Wooten said Wednesday that the company
planned to close offices in more than 30 of the 65 cities in which
its mortgage branch operates, and lay off 500 of its 2,650
employees. The company also cut nearly 1,000 employees last year.
   Although final decisions have not been made on which offices to
eliminate, several are expected to be in the Midwest and Southeast,
Wooten said.
   The company also said it plans to divest itself of a small,
virtually inactive home-building company, Braewood Homes of Dallas.
   Lomas' problems stem from a downturn in the housing industry
nationwide, which has slowed new mortgage originations.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association, a trade group, estimates there
will be between $320 billion and $330 billion in mortgages
originated nationwide in 1988, a decline from the $430 billion
originated in 1987.
   At the same time, more homeowners have fallen behind on their
payments, and more of the company's existing loans are delinquent,
Wooten said.
   ``By far the biggest portion of it (the restructuring) is the
result of bankruptcies and foreclosures that have just kept on
keeping on,'' he said. ``Rather than whittle it as you go, you've
got to build a reserve for it and start recovering from it.''
   Kenneth Campbell, an analyst with Audit Investments Inc. of
Montvale, N.J., said Lomas is not alone in its troubles.
   ``Other mortgage bankers are seeing the same thing. They've
either cut back on offices or staffing. The whole industry has been
slammed into reverse,'' he said.
</TEXT>
