<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BritishBanks     02-18 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-British Banks,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midland Bank Posts Loss Due To Third World Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midland Bank PLC, one of Britain's big four
commercial banks, said Thursday it suffered a huge loss during
1987, due to the October stock market crash and its decision to
raise its loan-loss provision to cover shaky Third World debt.
   The bank said it lost 456 million pounds, or about $798 million,
last year, compared with a net profit of about $424 million in 1986.
   Midland took a charge of $1.79 billion in the middle of last
year for an increase in its loan-loss provisions. But it said an
extraordinary gain of $110 million, on which it wouldn't elaborate,
helped narrow the 1987 loss.
   Excluding the loan-loss provision charge, Midland said, its
pre-tax profit would have been about $894 million.
   Several major U.S. banks also reported a severe drop in 1987
earnings or losses due to their decision to build up provisions for
loan losses. The banks' goal was to establish a cushion to protect
future earnings from loans that must be writen off or disposed of
at a loss.
   The action was taken after Brazil, the developing world's
biggest debtor, halted interest payments on its international bank
debt a year ago. The banks also cited continuing economic woes in
Third Wrold countries and a series of debt restructurings.
   Midland also said ``losses incurred by (the) institutional
equities business were ... a serious setback, but we believe our
investment banking operations as a whole weathered the financial
storms of 1987, especially the period since October,'' when
worldwide equity markets collapsed.
   Midland said it began a cost-cutting program at the end of last
year.
   In November, the bank announced that Hongkong & Shanghai Banking
Corp. would take a 14.9 percent stake in Midland and that the two
banks would collaborate on a number of activities.
   Last summer, the company sold additional stock.
</TEXT>
