<FILEID>AP-PX-02-18-88 1412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Goodrich     02-18 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Goodrich,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>B.F. Goodrich Announces 58 Percent Increase In Fourth-Quarter
Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   B.F. Goodrich Co. said Thursday its
fourth-quarter profit jumped 58 percent from a year earlier, partly
because of higher sales in its key polyvinyl chloride plastic
business.
   Goodrich said it earned $20.5 million, or 73 cents a share, in
the three months ended Dec. 31 compared with $13 million, or 51
cents a share, earned during the same period of 1986.
   Fourth-quarter sales were $567.3 million, compared with $491.3
million during the same period in 1986.
   Sales of polyvinyl chloride and intermediates rose 26.4 percent
to $273.4 million during the quarter, the company said in a news
release. Goodrich also reported a 25 percent boost in sales of
specialty chemicals, to $181.4 million.
   Sales of industrial products were down 36.4 percent, while sales
of aerospace and defense products dropped 4.7 percent, Goodrich
said.
   Rising polyvinyl chloride sales also were credited with more
than tripling Goodrich's annual profit, although total company
sales declined. Net income for 1987 was $105 million, or $4.06 a
share, compared with $32.7 million, or $1.32 a share, in 1986.
   Annual revenue fell to $2.2 billion from $2.5 billion in 1986.
   The 1986 results included $660 million in tire sales before the
formation of the company's Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co. joint venture.
   ``Our 1987 results are a clear confirmation that the
restructuring of the company is achieving the goals that were
previously set,'' said John D. Ong, Goodrich chairman and chief
executive officer.
   ``Our core businesses produced operating income at record levels
despite significantly increased investments in research and
development and in marketing,'' Ong said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880218-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-02-18-88 1423EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PostalCutbacks     02-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Cutbacks,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office Hops Cuts Will Save $160 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mail cutbacks, forced by federal budget
reductions, are starting to be felt by customers who are finding
some windows closed at post offices and their out-of-town mail
being delayed.
   Post offices dropped their third shift on Sundays starting last
weekend, said Postal Service spokeswoman Meg Harris. The group
works from about 3 p.m. to midnight and sorts mail bound to other
cities.
   The move is expected to save between $55 million and $60 million
toward covering the $160 million the agency has to absorb in cuts
in the current fiscal year, she said.
   In addition, $50 million is expected to be saved by closing post
office window services for a half-day a week, with the balance to
come from cuts in transportation, management travel, training and
other expenditures.
   Dropping the third-shift of mail processing on Sundays is
expected to primarily affect mail going out of town, said Harris.
She said Sundays were chosen for the cut because that is the day
when the least mail is deposited in the system.
   The first and second shifts, which generally sort mail for
delivery within the city where the office is located, are remaining
at work on Sundays, Harris said.
   The Postal Service closed most of its post offices on the
Saturdays following Christmas and New Year to cut costs, and now
has instituted a local program of closing a half-day a week. The
decision on when to close is being left to local managers.
   In general, postal managers have said they do not expect the
cutbacks to have a major effect on mail delivery, although
elimination of some sorting on Sunday could slow outgoing mail.
   Over the next 21 months the postal service will have to trim
$430 million from its operating budget and also has had to either
postpone or scrap $1.7 billion in capital construction and
purchasing because of the budget cuts imposed by Congress.
   There has been disagreement over how postal workers will be
affected. Postal officials have said they do not expect any
layoffs, while union leaders contend that the cutbacks could result
in loss of several thousand jobs nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
