<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Takeover,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Sells Societe Generale Stake To Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Royale Belge SA, a leading Belgian
insurance company, said Thursday it had sold its 3.75 percent stake
in Societe Generale de Belgique SA to Banque Generale du Luxembourg.
   A spokesman for Royale Belge declined to disclose the terms of
the sale.
   Societe Generale, Belgium's largest holding company, is the
target of a hostile takeover bid by Italian financier Carlo de
Benedetti.
   De Benedetti claims he controls 38 percent of Societe Generale's
28.2 million shares outstanding and has launched a bid for another
15 percent.
   Societe Generale closed at 4,920 francs a share on Thursday,
about $140.58, down from 5,000 francs on Wednesday.
   Royale Belge's main shareholders are Groupe Bruxelles Lambert
SA, which is Belgium's second largest holding company, and Union
des Assurances de Paris, a major French insurer.
   The Royale Belge spokesman said his company still had a small
stake in a Societe Generale unit Sodecom, which is a vehicle for a
contested share issue Societe Generale is trying to launch to
dilute De Benedetti's stake in the company.
</TEXT>
