<1ST_LINE>r f AM-InsiderTrading     02-18 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Enforcement Chief Quoted As Saying Heavy Penalties ImpedingNew
Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe insider-trading penalties are damaging
new cases by discouraging potential defendants from cooperating, a
top official of the Securities and Exchange Commission was quoted
as saying Thursday.
   Gary Lynch, SEC enforcement director and one of the architects
behind an aggressive campaign against Wall Street corruption, was
quoted as saying in an interview that the prospect of imprisonment,
civil fines and financial ruin is convincing some people ``it's
better to hunker down than cooperate.''
   It was unclear from Lynch's remarks whether he was suggesting
less stringent sanctions against insider trading, the illicit use
of nonpublic information to profit in securities transactions.
   Lynch spoke to ``The Wall Street Journal Report,'' a weekly
television program of business and financial news produced by Dow
Jones & Co., publisher of the Wall Street Journal.
   The company released a partial transcript of his remarks, to be
broadcast this Sunday, one year since the Feb. 20, 1987 sentencing
of Dennis B. Levine, a former investment banker whose arrest for
massive insider trading infractions spawned a widespread federal
investigation.
   Levine, who cooperated with the government, was forced to
relinquish $11.6 million in illicit profits. He received a criminal
punishment of two years imprisonment and a $362,000 fine.
   ``We're getting less cooperation today,'' Lynch was quoted as
saying in response to a question about what has changed in the past
year that has made the investigation easier or more difficult.
   ``More people are asserting their fifth amendment rights and not
cooperating,'' he was quoted as saying. ``So we're not able to ask
basic questions about contact, and that's certainly their
constitutional right, but it does make it more difficult to put
together information for an investigation.''
   Asked for further explanation, Lynch was quoted as saying: ``It
was one thing when people had to be concerned about a civil action
by the SEC and perhaps the disgorgement of money.
   ``It's another thing, when you talk about putting them out of
business completely and, not getting disgorgement of profits, but a
civil penalty as well and then subjecting them to the possibility
of time in federal prison. So, add it all up and some lawyers are
advising their clients: It's better to hunker down than cooperate.''
   Lynch was traveling abroad until Monday and unavailable to
comment about the interview, his office said.
   SEC spokeswoman Mary McCue, who didn't attend the interview,
said ``I've heard Gary say before that there is more hunkering
down, so I would not dispute that, but I don't know if I would make
that the greatest news release that ever hit the pike.''
   Levine's cooperation led investigators to Ivan F. Boesky, once
one of Wall Street's most powerful stock speculators. He paid a
record $100 million to settle civil charges of insider trading in
November 1986 and was sentenced to a three-year criminal term last
December.
   Although Boesky and Levine are said to have implicated a number
of other Wall Street professionals in illegal activity, there have
been no significant arrests in the past year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880218-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-PX-02-18-88 1438EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Taiwan-Trade Bjt   02-18 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Trade, Bjt,0893</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Pressure For Trade Concessions Changing Taiwan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwanese trade concessions made under
U.S. pressure are profoundly changing this prosperous island,
enraging businessmen who face stiffer competition and delighting
consumers who find lower price tags on foreign goods.
   The United States, which ran up a record trade deficit last
year, has pressured Taiwan to cut its hefty tariffs and revalue its
currency. Roughly one-tenth of the $171.2 billion U.S. deficit came
from trade with Taiwan.
   Since the United States is Taiwan's most important political
ally and receives nearly half of Taiwan's exports, Washington's
wishes cannot be ignored.
   ``We want to maintain our export market in the United States so
we must take more positive measures to help solve the trade
problems (between the two countries),'' Economic Affairs Minister
Lee Ta-hai told a recent legislative session.
   After decades of closely linking the Taiwan dollar to the U.S.
dollar, Taiwan authorities have allowed their currency to rise
about 40 percent against the U.S. dollar since January 1986.
   The changing exchange rate makes Taiwan goods more expensive
overseas and American products cheaper in Taiwan.
   Taiwan also recently reduced tariffs on 3,500 agricultural and
industrial products in a sweeping move that cut the average duty on
imported goods to an estimated 3.8 percent from 7.5 percent,
although tariffs on some goods remain much higher.
   U.S. officials, however, have indicated they want even further
trade concessions from Taiwan and Asia's other newly industrialized
countries _ Hong Kong, Singapore and South Korea. That upsets
Taiwanese who believe the trade concessions already have hurt the
country, whose exports account for 58 percent of gross national
product.
   In a poll conducted by the mass-circulation China Times and
published at the end of 1987, about 350 people out of nearly 1,000
interviewed chose the United States as the most unfriendly nation
to Taiwan. That was more than double the number of people who
picked Communist China, Taiwan's arch rival.
   ``Our 40 years of endeavors may be wiped out in these one or two
years,'' grumbled David Hong, president of K-Moebel Co., a sporting
goods manufacturer whose 140-member work force was cut in half to
reduce costs as the rising Taiwan dollar squeezed profits.
   Hong said the United States' decision in January to remove
duty-free and preferential tariffs on Taiwan products would make
business even more difficult.
   ``I am worried that mainland Chinese products, which will
continue to enjoy the preferential tariffs, may gradually take
over,'' he said.
   Businessmen argue that the Taiwan government has made too many
trade concessions too quickly under U.S. pressure, giving
labor-intensive local industries little time to adjust.
   Farmers also say the government has sacrificed their interests
to please the United States by cutting tariffs on farm products.
Thousands of farmers descended on Taipei last December to protest
sharply lowered fruit prices.
   But Taiwan's policy changes have not all been painful.
   Taiwan citizens generally welcome the government's tariff cuts
on a wide variety of foreign products, which have long been too
expensive for most people to afford.
   An estimated 8,000 American passenger cars were sold to Taiwan
last year, an eightfold increase from the year before but still
representing only 4 percent of the domestic market. Total imported
cars sales increased an estimated 35 percent.
   Imports of some American home appliances and many other goods
more than doubled last year. U.S. goods accounted for an estimated
5 percent of color televisions sold, 14 percent of refrigerators,
21 percent of washing machines and 8 percent of cigarettes.
   ``American cars are no longer considered as expensive, bulky and
gasoline-consuming. Many people are buying them now as the second
family car,'' said auto dealer Sherry Yang.
   Office managers, secretaries and salesmen armed with fatter
paychecks are buying Buicks, Skyhawks and Cieras that once were
only within the reach of the most wealthy. A Skyhawk sells for
about 700,000 Taiwan dollars, or $25,000, about 30 percent cheaper
than two years ago.
   ``Many people are finding for the first time they can afford
American products,'' said Dustine Wang, a dealer of Whirlpool,
General Electric and Westinghouse home appliances, which used to be
more than twice as expensive as local products.
   ``I did not hesitate at all in buying it,'' Wu Pei-pei said of
her new Whirlpool washer. ''I know it is more endurable, has a
larger capacity and not much more expensive'' than her old
Taiwan-made machine.
   Recent statistics indicate the trade gap is narrowing.
   Taiwan's January trade surplus of $843 million with the United
States was the lowest since February 1986.
   With its January exports of $1.2 billion, the United States
replaced Japan for the first time since 1963 as the country selling
the most goods to Taiwan.
   But the trade battle between the two countries is not yet
finished. Local newspapers, with dispatches from Washington, said
U.S. officials indicated they would ask Taiwan to further
appreciate its currency after the one-month state mourning period
for President Chiang Ching-kuo, who died Jan. 13 of heart failure.
   The local media also have reported that U.S. agricultural
officials have protested against planned measures by Taiwan
authorities to protect local farmers against foreign competition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
