<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AirFares     02-18 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Air Fares,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Announce Fare Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines has sparked a new
round of air fare increases by boosting some one-way coach fares by
$5 and first-class tickets by $10, effective Saturday, officials
said.
   Delta, United and Braniff airlines are among those who matched
the increases that American said Wednesday would affect most
tickets except advance-purchase fares, the cheapest available for
air travel.
   ``We felt that a slight, upward fare adjustment was economically
justified at this time,'' American spokesman Al Becker said at the
company's headquarters here.
   Houston-based Continental, which in the past year has served as
the industry's price leader, matched the fare hikes in a few
markets, said company spokesman Doug Birdsall.
   He said Continental will continue studying the markets where it
has not yet raised fares.
   The higher prices will affect mostly business travelers and
people traveling because of a personal emergency or some other
spur-of-the-moment reason, officials said.
   The price increases will affect:
   _Many coach and first-class fares for non-stop flights between
major cities, including Dallas, New York, Chicago, Kansas City,
Denver, San Francisco and Los Angeles.
   _Most unrestricted _ and unadvertised _ one-way discount fares.
   _Some round-trip discount fares with advance-purchase
requirements of up to 14 days and cancellation penalties of up to
50 percent.
   American's higher fares will mean, for example, that an
unrestricted coach ticket to Los Angeles or Washington, D.C., from
Dallas will cost $410 one way instead of $405. A discounted,
unrestricted coach ticket will cost $214 on those routes, up from
$209.
</TEXT>
