<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Retail     02-18 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Retail,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>J.C Penney, Carter Hawley Hale Report Strong Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. on Thursday reported an increase in its
fourth quarter profit despite a slight drop in sales, while another
major retailer, Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc., said it had
stronger second quarter earnings.
   Penney, based in New York, said net income for the three months
ended Jan. 30 rose 10 percent, to $280 million, or $1.93 a share,
from $253 million, or $1.80, during the same period a year ago.
   Sales totaled $4.94 billion, down from $4.98 billion.
   For its fiscal year, the giant retailer's net income totaled
$608 million, or $4.11 a share, on sales of $15.33 billion. That
compared with earnings of $478 million, or $3.53, and sales of
$14.74 billion.
   Los Angeles-based Carter Hawley netted $20.4 million, or 94
cents per share, on sales of $866 million for the three months
ended Jan. 30. A year ago, it lost $24.2 million on sales of $995.1
million, reflecting a major restructuring.
   The company earned $31.1 million, or $1.33 per share, during the
first half of its fiscal year, vs. a deficit of $7.8 million in the
previous year. Sales fell to $1.48 billion from $1.7 billion.
   Penney Chairman William R. Howell said the company's retail
operations achieved record results during 1987 despite fierce
competition during the lucrative Christmas holiday season. The
company's catalog operations also were especially strong throughout
the year, he said.
   Howell said Penney was able to cut many expenses during the
fiscal year, particularly in personnel and advertising. As a result
of the 1986 tax law, income taxes were cut by $17 million in the
fourth quarter, he said.
   Howell said the company was ``well positioned to respond to
consumer buying patterns'' in 1988.
   ``The expansion of women's apparel offerings and the continued
strengthening of men's and children's apparel will result in
significant opportunities for stores and catalog,'' he said in a
statement.
   Carter Hawley's results for last year included a loss of $29.3
million in both the quarter and half for early retirement of debt,
although this year's results reflected sharly higher interest
payments because of debt linked to its restructuring.
   As part of the restructuring, the company spun off its
higher-end specialty-store operations. It also sold its John
Wanamaker chain and two Broadway-Southwest stores in August 1987.
   Carter Hawley's stores include Broadway, Emporium Capwell,
Thalheimers and Weinstock's department stores.
</TEXT>
