<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TobaccoTrial     02-18 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tobacco Trial,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Tampering Alleged in Tobacco Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi police are investigating
allegations that American Tobacco Co. tampered with the jury in a
cigarette liability case that ended in a mistrial last month, the
Los Angeles Times reported Thursday.
   At issue are allegations that two employees of American's legal
defense team contacted three jurors during the trial, Frank
Carlton, district attorney for Mississippi's 4th Judicial District,
told the Times.
   Carlton said if the contacts did occur, they probably were
improper but not ``an outright attempt to ... affect the outcome of
the trial.''
   The allegations were made in affidavits gathered by attorneys
for the family of Nathan H. Horton, who died at age 50 of lung
cancer after smoking American's Pall Mall cigarettes for more than
30 years.
   Horton's family filed a $16.5 million suit in Lexington, Mass.,
against the cigarette maker. The suit ended in a hung jury Jan. 29.
   In the affidavits, two jurors said they were called during the
trial by employees of American Tobacco's legal team and and told of
a change in scheduling. Other affidavits said an American Tobacco
adviser boasted of receiving $2,700 for his work and was seen
talking to a third juror.
   The company's lead lawyer, James Upshaw, termed the affidavits
``absurb'' and ``an absolutely pathetic effort to get some type of
publicity.''
</TEXT>
