<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChemLawnSuit     02-18 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ChemLawn Suit,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abrams Sues Chemlawn Over Safety Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemlawn Services Corp., the Ohio-based lawn
care service, uses ``fraudulent, deceptive and illegal''
advertising regarding pesticide safety, the state attorney charged
Wednesday in a lawsuit calling for a halt to the ads and a fine for
false advertising.
   The lawsuit, filed in Manhattan State Supreme Court, charged
Chemlawn advertising made claims ``not supported by scientific
evidence or valid in only a narrow, technical sense.''
   The filing by Attorney General Robert Abrams came three weeks
after Chemlawn filed suit against the attorney general over his
allegations and asked a Supreme Court judge to determine whether
the advertising was misleading.
   The company and Abrams have been arguing for months over the
contents of Chemlawn advertising; the attorney general notified the
company in November of his impending lawsuit.
   ``We have a right to distribute accurate information about our
product,'' said Steve Hardymon, a Chemlawn spokesman. ``The
attorney general has been harassing us for the last year. We just
got tired of it, and asked a judge to make the final decision on
the ads.''
   Hardymon had not seen Abrams' filing Wednesday, and could not
comment on his specific charges.
   The attorney general alleged that because information is not
available about the chronic, long-term effects of many pesticides,
Chemlawn could not guarantee full safety.
   Abrams specifically cited one ad as false and misleading after
it promised, ``A person would have to ingest over 40 cupfuls of
lawn clippings treated with Chemlawn to equal the toxicity of a
single cup of coffee.''
</TEXT>
