<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 1040EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Venezuela     02-18 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela Foresees Trouble in Meeting International Payments This
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Venezuelan government foresees
trouble in making foreign loan payments this year but a top
government official denied Wednesday the country will seek new
terms for repaying $20 billion in refinanced debt.
   ``We will make every effort this year to prevent a significant
drop in international reserves, but this will depend on oil
prices,'' Finance Minister Hector Hurtado told a press conference.
   ``We think we can partially cover the oil price drop,'' Hurtado
said.
   Petroleos de Venezuela President Juan Chacin Guzman said
recently the state oil company will earn around $15 per barrel on
its oil exports in the first half of the year, or $1.70 less than
the company's $16.70 per barrel estimate for the year.
   The drop means around $1 billion less in oil income, according
to private estimates.
   The oil company originally estimated oil earnings this year of
$9.6 billion, while other exports could reach $1.3 billion.
   Hurtado said the government would be paying around $3.5 billion
this year in interest and principal on its $32 billion foreign
debt. It will amortize $400 million of refinanced debt.
   ``Renegotiations (on the refinanced debt) make no sense while we
continue to pay interest,'' Hurtado said.
   He said the drop in oil income will be partially covered by $300
million more from exports of aluminum and gold.
   The government will also press for multilateral loans and
foreign direct investment, and it is considering additional issues
of dollar-denominated bonds, he said.
   Last week the government launched a $100 million Eurobond issue
aimed at Venezuelan investors.
   The government recently reduced the private sector import budget
to around $7.2 billion but indicated there could be further cuts.
   The Central Bank's foreign reserves were $9.3 billion at
year-end 1987, including $3.5 billion of operating reserves.
   The nation is in technical default of its refinancing agreement
if operative reserves fall below $2 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
