<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EPICBailout     02-18 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPIC Bailout,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPIC Bailout Expected to Proceed Despite TMIC Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bailout plan in the $1.4 billion collapse
of real estate syndicator Equity Programs Investment Corp. is
expected to continue despite the financial problems of EPIC's major
mortgage insurer, officials said Wednesday.
   However, the decision last month by TMIC Insurance Corp. to halt
claims payments put into default 6,600 of EPIC's properties with
unpaid balances of $485 million. Deeds to those properties were
offered to lenders in lieu of foreclosure, said John Cross of
Skyline Financial Services Corp.
   That means the lender assumes ownership, rather than the
partnerships that had been formed by EPIC to buy the properties.
   Virginia-based Skyline has been hired to oversee the sale of
EPIC's properties. The number already had been reduced to 12,500
from 20,000 in the past two years before the TMIC default.
   Cross said the EPIC bailout was expected to proceed despite
TMIC's difficulties.
   Meanwhile, state Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie said
talks are under way between her agency, the Federal National
Mortgage Association (Fannie Mae) and private mortgage companies in
efforts to rescue TMIC and the EPIC bailout plan.
   A new actuarial study indicating how deep TMIC's troubles are is
expected to be completed later this month, Ms. Gillespie said
Wednesday.
   Fannie Mae, a major purchaser of mortgages from EPIC, was the
lead agency in arranging the EPIC bailout plan.
   TMIC is a subsidiary of the nation's leading title insurer,
Ticor, and has been operating under state conservatorship since
April 1986.
   The bulk of TMIC's problems stemmed from the collapse of EPIC.
   TMIC had insured about 45 percent of the 20,000 mortgages worth
$1.4 billion syndicated by EPIC as tax shelters for the
well-heeled. In 1985, EPIC defaulted on the mortgages and the
insurers were left holding the bag.
   Besides TMIC, two other major mortgage insurers had large
liabilities when EPIC collapsed: MGIC Investment Corp., a unit of
Milwaukee-based Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Co., and
Republic Mortgage Insurace, a unit of Chicago-based Old Republic
International Corp.
   Officials of MGIC and Republic said their companies were
continuing payments under the EPIC plan.
   EPIC, which was based in Falls Church, Va., was the real-estate
investment arm of Community Savings & Loan Association of Bethesda,
Md. In 1986, Community sought Chapter 11 protection from creditors
and subsequently was acquired by Mellon Bank of Pittsburgh, Pa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
