<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-18 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises in Domestic Trading, Gold Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar staged an unusual turnaround
Thursday, closing mostly lower in Europe but rising domestically on
technical factors and President Reagan's statement that he wants to
rescue a kidnap victim in Lebanon.
   Gold prices were mostly lower. Republic National Bank of New
York reported a late bid for gold of $442.80 a troy ounce, down
from Wednesday's late bid of $446.00.
   In European trading, the dollar finished lower against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar, with little news to affect
trading.
   Traders sold dollars in anticipation the U.S. currency would
fall through certain technical levels. But when the dollar failed
to cross those points, dealers had to buy back dollars to cover
their positions, pushing the currency higher in U.S. activity,
traders said.
   ``The markets weren't going anywhere, and people needed to buy
dollars back,'' said James O'Neill, a vice president and financial
market economist at Marine Midland Bank.
   Separately, traders said President Reagan's statement that he
wants to rescue Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, who was
kidnapped in Lebanon, sparked sudden interest in the dollar.
   ``The prospects of the U.S. going in with forces to get the
colonel out of Lebanon adds fuel to the fire because in the case of
war breaking out, the dollar is a safe haven,'' said Joseph Cally,
a trader at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Earlier, in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 130.00 Japanese yen,
down from 130.41. In London late Thursday, the dollar traded lower
at 129.72. Later in New York, the dollar rose to 130.375 yen from
130.125 yen Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7508 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.7490. In New York, it
cost $1.74175 to buy one pound, cheaper than Wednesday' $1.75415.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.71225 West German marks, up from 1.7010;
1.40965 Swiss francs, up from 1.3995; 5.7870 French francs, up from
5.7395; 1,261.00 Italian lire, up from 1,253.50, and 1.27055
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2673.
   Other dollar rates in Europe late Thursday, compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.7040 West German marks, down
from 1.7065; 1.4010 Swiss francs, down from 1.4030; 5.7555 French
francs, down from 5.7635; 1.9130 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9190;
1,254.625 Italian lire, down from 1,258.75; 1.2690 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2656.
   Gold bullion prices were mostly lower. The late bid price in
London was $444 a troy ounce, down from 446.00, but it was higher
in Zurich at $447.50 bid, up from $446.00. Hong Kong financial
markets were closed for the Chinese New Year holiday.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold closed at $442.90 a
troy ounce, down from $446 Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.43 bid a troy ounce,
up from $6.42. On the Comex, silver closed at $6.335 a troy ounce,
down from $6.43 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
