<FILEID>AP-PX-02-18-88 1802EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-18 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit-Taking Pulls The Plug On Livestock Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Livestock futures plummeted the limit allowed for daily trading
Thursday in a wave of profit-taking apparently prompted by weak
demand for beef and pork products.
   Futures prices also fell on most other commodity markets.
Precious metals, copper, grains and soybeans, energy futures and
stock-index futures all retreated.
   The Commodity Research Bureau index, a measure of the
performance of 21 commodities, fell 2.07 points, a fairly large
move for the indicator.
   Livestock and meat traders on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
had been ignoring the weakening cash markets for beef and pork
products, but their attitude changed abruptly on Thursday, analysts
said.
   ``We've had a horrible beef market for three weeks and it never
bothered anybody. Today it started bothering everybody,'' said
Charlie Richardson, an analyst in Denver for Lind-Waldock & Co.
   ``We had people start to take profits, and later in the day
everybody decided they wanted out,'' Richardson said.
   Analysts said there had been no change in market fundamentals.
   ``The profit-taking kind of fed on itself,'' said Roger Norem,
an analyst for Agri-Visor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill. ``We
had quite a few orders to get out of long (buy) positions at the
close, and that carried over into the pork complex.''
   The selling caused limit-down moves of 1.50 cents a pound in
some live cattle, feeder cattle and hog contracts and 2 cents a
pound in some contracts for future delivery of frozen pork bellies.
   Live cattle settled .53 cent to 1.50 cents lower with the
February contract, which expires Friday, at 71.27 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .10 cent to 1.50 cents lower with March at 82.50
cents a pound; hogs were .48 cent to 1.50 cents lower with February
at 46.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .60 cent to 2.00
cents lower with February at 53.70 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures registered substantial declines on the
Commodity Exchange in New York after gold for April delivery passed
the psychologically important level of $450 a troy ounce only to
encounter strong resistance at $451.40, analysts said.
   The subsequent price decline was ``a very typical reaction to a
market that breaks out and fails to follow through,'' said Craig
Sloane, an analyst in New York for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Gold settled $3.10 to $3.50 lower with April at $445.80 a troy
ounce; silver was 9.5 cents to 10 cents lower with March at $6.35 a
troy ounce.
   Copper futures fell sharply on the Comex, with the March
contract settling 5.75 cents lower at 98.75 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures settled mostly lower in a modest
sell-off on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybeans led the decline in reaction to reduced demand for
soybean meal, analysts said. Many traders also took profits after
Wednesday's sharp advance in soybean futures, analysts said.
   Increased farmer selling of soybeans also pressured futures
prices, but the losses were limited by news of new soybean oil
sales to India and expectations for more export business, said
Richard Loewy, an analyst in New York for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   ``Based on the profit-taking which could have ensued, you're
still looking at good underlying strength'' in the soybean market,
Loewy said.
   Corn prices followed soybeans lower, while wheat prices
retreated on expectations of adequate near-term supplies, he said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cent to 6 cents lower with March at $3.21} a
bushel; corn was unchanged to 1{ cents lower with March at $2.00} a
bushel; oats were \ cent lower to \ cent higher with March at
$1.91} a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 6 cents lower with March
at $6.28{ a bushel.
   Unleaded gasoline led energy futures prices lower on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   Jim Ritterbusch of PaineWebber Inc. said crude oil supplies were
abundant while demand for gasoline and heating oil was weak.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .13 cent to .19 cent
lower with March at $16.45 a barrel; heating oil was .50 cent to
.73 cent lower with March at 45.08 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .69 cent to 1.30 cents lower with March at 45.97 a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 1.55 points lower at 258.30. The
underlying spot index was up 1.30 points at 257.91.
</TEXT>
