<1ST_LINE>u f BC-MoneySupply 1stLd-Writethru   02-18 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Money Supply, 1st Ld - Writethru,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Basic Money Supply Falls $3.4 Billion In Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTs 2 new grafs after 5th graf pvs The Fed...to UPDATE
with M2 and M3 figures. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The Fed...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's basic money supply fell by $3.4
billion in mid-February, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure of money known as M1 fell to a
seasonally adjusted $760.7 billion in the week ended Feb. 8 from
$764.1 billion the previous week. M1 includes cash in circulation,
deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M1 averaged $754.7 billion, a 1.9
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks.
   Analysts said the latest figure was within the range expected by
a number of economists, and as such had little effect on the bond
market.
   The Fed last year stopped setting a specific growth target range
for M1 because of doubts that the measurement accurately reflected
underlying economic activity. Instead, the Fed indicated, it was
more closely monitoring broader monetary aggregates known as M2 and
M3, exchange rates and other economic indicators.
   On Thursday, the Fed began reporting M2 and M3 on a weekly
instead of monthly basis. M2 fell $1.8 billion in the week ended
Feb. 8 to a seasonally-adjusted $2.94 trillion, and M3 fell $2.1
billion to an adjusted $3.712 trillion.
   M2 is made up of M1 and such accounts as savings deposits and
money-market mutual funds. M3 is the sum of M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   The Fed on Thursday also released its benchmark revisions to the
monetary aggregates for 1987.
   The central bank said M1 growth in 1987 was 6.2 percent, revised
from 5.9 percent; M2 growth was 4.0 percent, revised from 4.1
percent, and M3 growth was unrevised at 5.4 percent.
   The Fed had set a growth target range of 5.5 percent to 8.5
percent for M2 and M3. The actual growth was the slowest in those
aggregates since the Fed began targeting growth in 1979.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $368 million in
the week ended Feb. 10, compared with a gain of $87 million a week
earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said discount window bank borrowings from
the Federal Reserve System averaged $254 million daily in the week
ended Wednesday, up from $118 million during the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $272.4 billion in the two-week period ended
Feb. 10, down from $272.9 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
