<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-FarmCredit     02-18 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Farm Credit,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Credit System Reports Profit In Quarter, But Loss For Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Farm Credit System said it earned a profit
of $179 million in the final quarter of 1987, but posted a loss for
the full year in spite of a big reduction in its reserve for loan
losses.
   The loss of $17 million for all of 1987 was a fraction of the
losses of $2.7 billion in 1985 and $1.9 billion in 1986.
   The Farm Credit System said its interest income fell because of
competition from other lenders and a general decline in the demand
for agricultural loans. On the positive side, the system said it
was able to reduce the amount of money set aside for possible loan
losses because of ``continued improvement in the general
agricultural economy and the increased capacity of farmers and
ranchers to service their debt.''
   Loan-loss reserves were decreased by $684 million during the
year, to $2.95 billion at the end of 1987 from $3.64 billion at the
end of 1986.
   The Farm Credit System is a 71-year-old group of 37 banking
cooperatives and nearly 400 local lending associations. It was hit
hard by weakness in the agricultural economy.
   Bailout legislation signed into law last year created a private
assistance corporation that is authorized to issue up to $4 billion
in government-backed loans to financially troubled institutions in
the system.
   Interest on the loans will be paid initially by the government,
although the Farm Credit System would eventually pay everything
back.
   The Farm Credit System said its profit of $179 million in the
fourth quarter came on total interest income of $1.46 billion. In
the year-earlier period, the system had a loss of $384 million on
total interest income of $1.65 billion.
   In all of 1987, the Farm Credit System's loss of $17 million
came on total interest income of $5.78 billion, in contrast to a
year-earlier loss of $1.91 billion on total interest income of
$7.17 billion.
   The strong fourth-quarter results are not indicative of
expectations for 1988, the Farm Credit System said, because they
include a chunk of interest income from previous periods that was
not previously recorded.
   The results were also boosted by one-time reductions in
loan-loss provisions.
   The reduction in the provision for loan losses, partly offset by
some actual losses, added $207 million to the system's bottom line
in the fourth quarter and added $196 million to the bottom line in
all of 1987.
   In contrast, new provision for loan losses had subtracted $356
million from the bottom line in the fourth quarter of 1986 and
subtracted $1.80 billion from the bottom line in all of 1986.
   Price Waterhouse, the system's independent accountants, issued
an opinion on the statement that was qualified because of questions
surrounding the implementation of the federal bailout.
   ``The successful and timely implementation of the 1987 act is
dependent on several factors, many of which are outside the control
of the system,'' the Farm Credit System said in a news release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
