<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CorporateLiability     02-18 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corporate Liability,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Signs Corporate Liability Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer signed into law
Thursday bills giving top corporate officials greater protection
from lawsuits filed by disgruntled stockholders.
   Schaefer had sought the legislation to enhance the state's
business climate and to prevent some Maryland-based companies from
moving their headquarters to neighboring states that offer such
protection to officers and directors.
   As of Jan. 1, some 35 states had enacted laws offering some
degree of immunity from stockholder suits and are actively using
such laws to sell their states to companies considering
reincorporation, said Alan Rifkin, Schaefer's top legislative aide.
   ``This says something to business,'' Schaefer said as he signed
two identical bills passed at morning sessions of both the House
and Senate.
   ``It says we're interested in working together for the good of
the state,'' he said.
   The measures are specifically aimed at lawsuits brought by
stockholders who believe a business decision by an officer or
director was responsible for a drop in the value of a company's
stock.
   Business leaders strongly supported the measures, telling
lawmakers that skyrocketing liability insurance premiums have made
it increasingly difficult to attract quality business people to
serve on boards of directors.
   The Schaefer administration introduced a bill for the same
purpose last year, but it was rejected by the House Judiciary
Committee, reportedly because 1987's version did not give
stockholders the right to reject such immunity for its officers and
directors.
   The bill signed Thursday requires formal ratification of the
immunity provision by stockholders. The law also specifies that
such protection does not apply to lawsuits brought by third parties.
   Under the new law, which went into effect immediately after
Schaefer signed the bills, such immunity is lost when an officer or
director receives an improper financial benefit or in cases
involving deliberate dishonesty by a top corporate official.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
