<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp     02-18 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees No Recession; Factory Use Flat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration, proposing a $1.1 trillion federal
budget on Thursday, predicted the economy would continue to grow
without threat of recession.
   In other economic news, the Federal Reserve said the nation's
industrial operating rate was unchanged in January at 82.2 percent
of capacity, remaining at the highest level in almost eight years.
   In the financial markets, the stock market gave ground in late
trading Thursday and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
dropped below 2,000, falling 14.58 to 1,986.41. Bond prices and the
dollar edged higher.
   In its 1989 budget request, the administration foresaw no storm
clouds on the economic horizon, contending growth would slow during
the first half of 1988 but then rebound to robust levels in 1989
and beyond.
   The administration's economic forecasts, which provide the
underpinning for its assumptions on revenues and spending in the
budget, have been attacked in the past as rosy scenarios which bore
little resemblance to reality.
   But this year's version was greeted with less skepticism,
although it was still more optimistic than the outlook prepared by
the Congressional Budget Office and most private economists.
   ``In the last couple of years, the administration has lightened
the tint on their rose-colored glasses although their outlook is
still a lot rosier than we think is justified,'' said David Wyss,
an economist with Data Resources Inc., an economic forecasting firm.
   The administration derided as greatly exaggerated recession
fears stirred by the record 508-point drop in the New York Stock
Exchange's Dow Jones industrial average on Oct. 19 and contended
the economy had escaped with ``few signs of serious damage.''
   The administration predicted the gross national product, the
total output of goods and services, would expand at a modest rate
of 2.4 percent this year, down from 3.8 percent growth in 1987,
when measured from the fourth quarter of 1986.
   Congressional analysts are forecasting lower growth of 1.8
percent in 1988 and Wyss said Data Resources has just scaled back
its own GNP forecast to 1.4 percent, a full percentage point below
the administration.
   In the capacity utilization report, the Federal Reserve said
cutbacks in the production of steel and autos offset gains in other
areas, the government reported Thursday.
   The January operating rate remained at the highest level in
almost eight years, but it was the first month since September that
the operating rate had failed to move up.
</TEXT>
