<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM-Alda,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-MASH Star Hired for New IBM Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp., which has
assembled an ensemble of actors from the ``M-A-S-H'' television
series for its advertising, said Thursday it has signed the star of
that popular program.
   IBM said that Alan Alda, who starred as Hawkeye Pierce in
``M-A-S-H,'' signed a multiyear agreement earlier this month to
appear in commercials for the computer and office systems giant.
   The company declined to disclose how much Alda was being paid.
   The first ads featuring Alda will appear Saturday during
ABC-TV's Olympics broadcasts, IBM said. He will initially appear
alone in IBM ads.
   In one commercial, Alda paddles about a flooded office and
describes how an IBM service team worked without stop to restore a
customer's computer operations.
   He says IBM can help customers face the future in another ad,
and describes in a third commercial how the company can help
businesses of all sizes.
   Dave McGovern, an advertising executive for IBM, said the
company eventually plans to work Alda into ads that feature other
former members of the ``M-A-S-H'' cast.
   IBM launched advertising for its new family of Personal System 2
computers featuring seven former ``M-A-S-H'' cast members last
April, including Gary Burghoff who played Radar O'Reilly, Harry
Morgan who was Col. Sherman Potter and Loretta Swit who played Hot
Lips Houlihan. For IBM, they played the roles of co-workers in an
office.
   Conspicuously absent from that group was Alda, who reportedly
was still under contract to another computer company, Atari Corp.
   McGovern said IBM had been interested in having Alda appear in
its ads for some time, but that Alda had other commitments that
were preventing it.
   A call was placed to Alda's agent, but was not returned.
   McGovern said Alda continues to be widely recognized and is well
liked by the public although the ``M-A-S-H'' program creators and
actors have disbanded and the show has gone into reruns.
   He said Alda has done little advertising and said his
appearances for Atari occurred five years ago and should not
diminish his effectiveness for IBM.
   ``You don't have a sense that he is saying anything he doesn't
believe in,'' said Barry Hoffman, a creative director for the ad
agency Lord, Geller, Federico, Einstein Inc., which created the IBM
ads.
   McGovern said the ads using the former ``M-A-S-H'' actors have
scored better than the industry average with the public.
   IBM has said that it did not set out to reassemble the
``M-A-S-H'' cast for its ads. Among those from that program who are
missing from the IBM ensemble are McLean Stevenson, who played Col.
Henry Blake.
   McGovern declined to speculate on whether any new characters
would be added to the IBM ads. ``Stay tuned for further
developments,'' he said.
</TEXT>
