<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children's television advocates in the House
and Senate introduced legislation Thursday designed to rid the
airwaves of programs that feature toy manufacturers' products as
the central characters.
   ``Children's TV has been grossly overcommercialized,'' said Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, sponsor of the Senate measure. ``You
flip the dial and you'll find toys _ Lady Lovelylocks, ThunderCats,
Inhumanoids, GI Joe _ all starring in their own shows.''
   Since the Federal Communications Commission in 1984 scrapped its
commercial limits on children's TV shows, at least 70 programs that
critics call ``program-length commercials'' have appeared on
television, he said.
   Such programs are nothing more than ``sophisticated marketing
strategies aimed at kids,'' he said.
   ``I just say that's absurd and it's wrong. The airwaves belong
to the people of this country and they're being abused,'' he said
at a news conference attended by other members of the House and
Senate and organized by Action for Children's Television.
   The legislation was attacked by the National Association of
Broadcasters, which called it ``anachronistic, unnecessary,
inappropriate and ineffective,'' and said it raises First Amendment
questions.
   The NAB said toy-based programs are not commercials and not
subject to government regulation. ``Does the federal government
want to eliminate the Disney, Sesame Street and Charlie Brown
programs?'' NAB said.
   Metzenbaum's bill would restore the FCC's previous guidelines
that limited ads on children's shows to 9{ minutes per hour on
weekends and 12 minutes per hour on weekdays.
   A similar House bill also would reinstate the limits and in
addition would require TV stations to provide seven hours per week
of educational programming for young viewers.
   ``We can make children's television better,'' said Rep. Terry
Bruce, D-Ill., who co-sponsored the House measure with Reps. John
Bryant, D-Texas, and Edward Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the House
telecommunications subcommittee.
   The FCC, in response to a federal appeals court ruling last
June, is reviewing its children's TV policies and is considering
whether ad limits are needed and whether toy-based shows constitute
program-length commercials.
   But Markey said Congress will not wait for the FCC to act.
   ``The commission clearly has demonstrated that it cannot be
trusted to protect children from commercial exploitation,'' said
Markey, who has crossed swords with the FCC over many broadcasting
issues. ``When it comes to children's programming, this commission
has never found an offensive practice that it did not like.''
   Charren said her group has been concerned for years that
commercial considerations dominate programming decisions regarding
children's TV, making it difficult to get stations to devote time
to educational and informational shows for kids.
   Spencer Boise, a vice president of Mattel Inc., which makes a
dozen different toys on which cartoon shows are based, said the
programs are not commercials because the toys themselves are not
shown and ads for the toys never appear during or adjacent to the
program featuring the toy's cartoon character.
   ``It's an entertainment concept,'' he said. ``The characters are
shown in cartoon or animated form, not static form like the toys.''
   Markey said the content of many of the toy-based programs for
children would be classified as commercial time and, with ad
limitations in place, would be driven off the air.
   ``There will be certain clear areas where it will be
indisputably evident to all who witness it that a seamless fabric
connecting commercials to program content has been developed,'' he
said.
   ``We may reach some gray areas where there is a more open
question, but clearly there is going to be an overwhelming
consensus in the bulk of the areas ... that will be very difficult
for anyone to deny that products are actually seeking to be
promoted as part of the program content,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
