<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of striking employees at Ford Motor
Co.'s British plants voted to accept a two-year contract offer,
signaling the end of the country's first major industrial strike in
three years.
   The offer represented the first significant union victory in
Britain in seven years. Ford made several concessions to end the
strike, which began Feb. 8.
   Voter returns Thursday night showed 70 percent of the workers at
the 22 British plants favored the offer. The company said it
expected workers to be back on the job Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. plans to sell a stake of about 50
percent in its extensive U.S. gulf coast refining operations to
Saudi Arabia for more than $1 billion, according to published
reports.
   A final agreement between Petromin, the Saudi Arabian oil
holding arm, and Texaco is expected to be reached within a month,
the Herald Tribune reported Thursday, quoting an unidentified
Texaco executive and unidentified Arab oil executives attending an
annual conference of the Institute of Petroleum in London.
   In White Plains, N.Y., a spokesman at Texaco's headquarters
refused to confirm or deny the accuracy of the report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc.'s board of directors
approved a multibillion-dollar recapitalization plan, escalating
the company's battle to thwart the hostile $2.03 billion takeover
bid by Black & Decker Corp.
   The plan approved Thursday would pay American Standard
stockholders $64 a share in cash and junk bonds and give them stock
in the recapitalized company, which would take on a staggering new
debt load to finance the proposal.
   American Standard shares rose 50 cents to $67.50 and Black &
Decker dipped 12{ cents to $18.87{ on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe insider-trading penalties are damaging
new cases by discouraging potential defendants from cooperating, a
top official of the Securities and Exchange Commission was quoted
as saying.
   Gary Lynch, SEC enforcement director and one of the architects
behind a campaign against Wall Street corruption, was quoted as
saying in a television interview that the prospect of imprisonment,
civil fines and financial ruin is convincing some people ``it's
better to hunker down than cooperate.'' His remarks were to be
broadcast Sunday on ``The Wall Street Journal Report.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have ordered an immediate
suspension of the use of an industrial device which has leaked tiny
particles of radioactive polonium at plants around the nation.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission also ordered the 3M Corp. on
Thursday to recall for inspection all 45,000 of the suspect
devices, ionizing air guns used to control static electricity and
remove dust from product containers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks declined in late trading Thursday. The Dow Jones
industrial average dropped 14.58 points to 1,986.41 after closing
slightly above 2,000 in the week's first two sessions.
   Bond prices rose in reaction to falling commodity prices. The
dollar closed lower in Europe but higher in the United States. Gold
prices were mostly down.
</TEXT>
